I would use the chrome.storage.sync.set API  [chrome.storage.api][1].  You could set your text that searched and store it in a variable, then everytime you use the extension, you can have it reference that variable.  Without any code, I&#39;m going off of my own experience.  So I&#39;m including a bit of my example to show you how I used the chrome.storage api, so that maybe you could find it useful as well.

Here&#39;s a snippet of my code, it is a chrome extension that adds a url to the local storage so that way when I log into a firewall, I don&#39;t have to continually copy the string/text I&#39;m wanting to input.  

    function cfs_add(){
    var url = prompt(&#39;Please provide url&#39;, &#39;test.com&#39;);
    chrome.storage.sync.set({&#39;name&#39;: url}, function() {
      console.log(&quot;saved url!!&quot; );
    });
    };
    cfs_add()
    
